  "prompt": "What does \"net 30\" mean vs. \"due in 30 days\"?",
  "response": "\"Net 30\" and \"due in 30 days\" are terms used in invoicing and refer to the payment deadline for the invoice.\n\n**Net 30:**\n- This term means that the payment is due in full within 30 days from the invoice date.\n- It is commonly used in business transactions to provide the buyer with a specific period to pay for the goods or services received.\n\n**Due in 30 days:**\n- This phrase also indicates that the payment is required within 30 days.\n- However, it can sometimes be interpreted as 30 days from the date the invoice was received or processed, rather than strictly from the invoice date.\n\nIn practice, both terms usually mean the same thing: payment is expected within 30 days of the invoice date. However, \"Net 30\" is a more standardized term in business accounting and invoicing.",
